    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. To clarify, the reason we need to add rebar to concrete foundations is due to the difference in tensile and compressive strength between the two materials.\n\nConcrete has a high compressive strength, which is the ability to withstand forces that push it together. However, its tensile strength is relatively low, meaning it can't withstand forces that pull it apart. This is because concrete fibers are aligned in a specific direction, making them more prone to tensile failure.\n\nSteel rebar, on the other hand, has a high tensile strength, which allows it to resist forces that pull it apart. When embedded in the concrete, the rebar provides a continuous tensile reinforcement, helping to distribute the stress and prevent the concrete from cracking or failing.\n\nThink of it like a garrison of goblins trying to breach a wall - the concrete is strong against the goblins' compressive attacks, but the rebar is like a group of goblin-slayers who can withstand the goblins' tensile attacks and hold the wall together.",
